Patch Set 4:

Looking at the request being made in the bug report:

 [{"op": "remove", "path": "/something-non-existent-property/and-another-one", "value": "anydata"}]

it looks like the 'remove' operation has been given a value -- which may be bad syntax?

If so, should we be validating the request syntax and returning a 400 irrespective of whether the property exists or not if a value is supplied?

(In addition to correctly handling an attempted removal of a non-existant property).

It would be interesting to compare v2 behaviour here. Eg (1) what happens in v2 if you supply a value to the property delete request? (2) What happens in v2 if you try to delete a non-existing property?

Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

Also, note that the operation in the bug is 'remove' rather than 'replace'. It would be good to also cover that in the tests.
Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1 -Workflow

Patch Set 4:

Also, (3) what happens if you try to update a non-existant property in v2? eg Does it just get created and set to the value?

Patch Set 4:

V2
(1) Supply a value to a property delete: It just ignores it and deletes the value.
(2) Deleting a non-existing property: Returns a 409 (Conflict).
(3) Update a non-existing property: 
       (3a) add operation: overwrites if a values, else adds it in.
       (3b) replace operation: overwrites if a value exists, else returns a 409.
